    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-07-27T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-07-27T05:00:00-05:00" n="413"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d413">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.151/144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Aldridge</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-27T12:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 27, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received July 27—8:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>105. My July 12 [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>] 2 p.m. At the request of Mr. Maximos,
                    to whom I had fully explained the Ulen difficulties as soon as he became Foreign
                    Minister, I took Mr. Shepperd<note n="35" xml:id="d413fn35">Thomas S. Shepperd,
                        of Ulen &amp; Co.</note> personally to the Foreign Office yesterday and the
                    two men worked out a compromise agreement. The agreement was a verbal one and
                    was not worked out in complete detail, as it was reached an hour before Mr.
                    Shepperd left for the United States. For the time being, however, it apparently
                    settles the company’s difficulties and Mr. Shepperd has expressed his
                        satisfaction.<note n="36" xml:id="d413fn36">In despatch No. 797, August 28,
                        1935, the Chargé in Greece reported that written agreements dated August 16,
                        1935, were concluded in accordance with the previous verbal arrangement with
                        Mr. Shepperd (868.151/150).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Aldridge</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
